PROJECT NARRATIVE (HRSA 10‑PAGE FORMAT)

---

I. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

Open Arms is a statewide maternal health and family preservation initiative designed to stabilize pregnant women at imminent risk of newborn foster care placement. The program integrates OB/GYN services, WHNP‑led Centering Pregnancy, CNM‑led routine deliveries, addiction medicine, psychiatric care, trauma‑informed therapy, and social services within a 24/7 residential setting.

This midwifery‑inclusive model aligns with HRSA’s Maternal and Child Health (MCH) priorities by expanding access to prenatal care, reducing maternal morbidity, supporting culturally responsive birthing options, and lowering costs through evidence‑based, collaborative practice.

---

II. STATEMENT OF NEED

II.A Maternal Health Disparities in Louisiana

Louisiana ranks among the highest in the nation for maternal morbidity and mortality, particularly among women experiencing poverty, behavioral health conditions, and limited access to prenatal care. Pregnant women with substance use disorders or untreated mental illness face significant barriers to care, resulting in late or inconsistent prenatal engagement.

II.B Medicaid‑Mandated Toxicology Screening

State Medicaid programs require urine drug screening at the first prenatal visit. Positive toxicology results trigger mandatory DCFS reports, often leading to prenatal investigations, court involvement, and potential newborn removal. Without coordinated intervention, these women struggle to meet court‑ordered requirements.

II.C Fragmented Services

Existing services are siloed and outpatient. Transportation barriers, unstable housing, and untreated behavioral health conditions contribute to missed appointments and perceived non‑compliance. Few programs provide integrated prenatal care, addiction treatment, mental health services, and social services in a single setting.

II.D Lack of Midwifery‑Inclusive Models

Louisiana lacks residential programs that incorporate:

• WHNP‑led prenatal care
• CNM‑led low‑risk deliveries
• Water births and holistic birthing options
• Trauma‑informed labor support


These services are cost‑effective, evidence‑based, and strongly aligned with HRSA’s emphasis on expanding access to high‑quality maternal care in underserved populations.

---

III. PROJECT DESCRIPTION

III.A Program Overview

Open Arms is a 24/7 residential facility providing integrated medical, behavioral health, and social services to pregnant women referred by courts, DCFS, hospitals, and Medicaid providers. Length of stay spans pregnancy through early postpartum discharge planning.

III.B Core Components

III.B.1 Integrated Medical Care (HRSA Priority)

Open Arms provides a comprehensive maternal health model that includes:

• OB/GYN oversight for high‑risk pregnancies
• WHNP‑led Centering Pregnancy prenatal care
• CNM‑led routine vaginal deliveries
• Support for birthing plans including water births and low‑intervention labor
• On‑site pharmacy services
• Nutrition counseling
• Postpartum follow‑up and continuity of care


This model expands access, reduces costs, and supports maternal autonomy.

---

III.B.2 Addiction & Behavioral Health Treatment (SAMHSA Priority)

• Addictionologist‑led treatment
• Medication‑assisted treatment (as appropriate)
• Trauma‑informed individual and group therapy
• Domestic violence support
• Psychiatric evaluation and medication management


---

III.B.3 Social Services & Case Management (DOJ Priority)

• Individualized service plans aligned with court and DCFS requirements
• Coordination with child welfare, probation, and family court
• Parenting education
• Benefits and documentation support


---

III.B.4 Education & Workforce Development

• Industry‑based credentialing
• Tutoring and study hours
• Career readiness workshops
• Job placement coordination


---

III.B.5 Life Skills & Family Preservation

• Parenting classes
• Financial literacy
• Healthy relationships
• Peer support


---

III.B.6 Discharge & Re‑Entry Planning

• Housing placement
• Employment pathways
• Postpartum care plan
• Warm handoff to WHNP/CNM community providers
• Reunification planning


---

IV. STAFFING PLAN

IV.A Medical & Clinical Staff

Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP)

Leads Centering Pregnancy groups, provides routine prenatal care, conducts screenings, manages prenatal documentation, and ensures continuity of care. Serves as a primary clinical provider for pregnant participants.

Certified Nurse Midwife (CNM)

Provides midwifery‑led prenatal care and conducts low‑risk vaginal deliveries. Supports birthing autonomy, including water births and holistic birthing plans. Collaborates with OB/GYN for high‑risk cases.

OB/GYN Provider

Provides oversight for high‑risk pregnancies, collaborates with WHNP and CNM, and ensures clinical safety.

Addictionologist

Provides SUD treatment and MAT oversight.

Psychiatrist/PMHNP

Provides psychiatric evaluation and medication management.

Registered Nurses (24/7)

Provide daily health assessments, medication administration, and crisis support.

Licensed Therapists

Provide trauma‑informed therapy and domestic violence support.

---

V. DAILY SCHEDULE

A structured daily schedule includes medical check‑ins, therapy, prenatal care, credentialing coursework, case management, life‑skills classes, and evening recovery groups. Quiet hours begin at 9:00 PM with 24/7 staff coverage.

---

VI. REFERRAL PATHWAY

VI.A Medicaid‑Mandated Screening

Positive prenatal toxicology results require DCFS notification, triggering risk assessment and potential court involvement.

VI.B Referral Sources

• DCFS
• Family courts
• OB/GYNs and hospitals
• Probation
• Medicaid providers


VI.C Admission Process

Includes clinical intake, review of toxicology results, and coordination with courts for placement orders.

---

VII. ORGANIZATIONAL CAPACITY

Open Arms is led by Dr. Steffany Windham and governed by a board with expertise in healthcare, behavioral health, child welfare, and nonprofit management. The organization maintains EHR systems, data tracking tools, and partnerships with hospitals, workforce boards, and community agencies.

---

VIII. EVALUATION PLAN

VIII.A Key Performance Indicators

Maternal Health Indicators

• % receiving WHNP‑led prenatal care
• % completing Centering Pregnancy
• % CNM‑led low‑risk vaginal deliveries
• % achieving preferred birthing plan
• Reduction in unnecessary cesarean sections
• Reduction in maternal morbidity


Family Preservation Indicators

• Custody retention at birth
• Reduction in newborn foster care placements


Behavioral Health Indicators

• Reduction in substance use
• Engagement in therapy
• Improved mental health assessments


Economic Stability Indicators

• Credential completion
• Employment or training enrollment
• Housing stability


---

VIII.B Data Collection

• EHR
• Case notes
• Toxicology screenings
• Court/DCFS reports
• Participant surveys


---

VIII.C Reporting

Monthly internal reviews, quarterly funder reports, and annual evaluation summaries.

